ally shifted to Arabic-Islamic themes. Yet his early Jewish program remained encoded in his new scholarly pursuits. Islamic studies was a refuge for him from his grievances with the Jewish establishment; from local academic and social irritations he found comfort in his international network of colleagues. This intellectual and academic transformation is explored in the book in three dimensions – scholarship on religion, in religion (Judaism and Islam), and as religion – utilizing his diaries, correspondences and his little-known early Hungarian works.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aGoldziher, Ignác *1850-1921*. 4aIslamwissenschaft. 4aJudaistik. 4aOrientalistik. 4aWissenschaft des Judentums. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aArabic Scholarship.  aBudapest Jewry.  aHistory of Jewish Studies.  aHistory of Oriental Studies.  aHungarian Jewish history.  aHungarian Orientalism.  aIgnaz Goldziher.  aIslamic Scholarship.  aNeolog Judaism.  aRabbinical Seminaries.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z97831111757820 cEPUBz97831107415750 cprintz978311074010340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311074128540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110741285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110741285/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK